1.body: Before you start working on any projects, you should create folders to store your project files. I would like you to use a specific structure for a few reasons: I will give you test code for the Guided Projects. This test code expects your projects to be organized a certain way. You may not be able to run the tests if you don't organize your projects as shown below. When I download projects from Blackboard, I process them automatically with some scripts. This saves me hours of organizing and renaming everyone's files throughout the semester. My scripts also handle testing the Guided Projects, and they'll use the same test code I give you. If your submission isn't organized correctly, then my scripts will not be able to extract the project files and run the relevant tests, and your submission will be marked incomplete. Keeping your work organized will make it easier for you to keep track of everything.

├── final/

Each folder name must only contain lowercase letters, and the spelling must match exactly what is shown above. Ignore the / at the end of each name, this is to indicate that the name refers to a directory rather than a regular file. You can create these directories by hand from your file browser, but it's easier to use the terminal. The following commands create all dozen or so folders with the correct names, and they will work in most Mac/Linux terminals. If you're on Windows, then read the terminal section of the notes and follow the directions for getting a terminal emulator that can run bash commands. The default Windows terminals (cmd and powershell) will not be able to run most bash commands. mkdir projects
cd projects
mkdir -p final tests logs project{1,2,3}/part{1,2} project{1,2}/part3 The name of the root folder (projects) doesn't technically matter, so you can use a different name. Just change the name projects in the first two commands to your new folder name, but make sure it doesn't contain any spaces. The tests and logs folders are used by my test code. When you download the test code, you will extract the contents to the projects/tests folder. Every time you run a test, it will leave a log file in the projects/logs folder with a more detailed record of the test. These logs are useful when you cannot determine why your code is failing a test or if you encounter a bug in my test code. I may ask you to send me the log file from a test if you ask me to help you figure out why your code isn't passing.

23.body:
A Guided Project program must meet the following I/O requirements: The program accepts the required input in the order shown in the assignment and does not expect any additional input. The program produces each line of required output in the order specified in the assignment. The program may include additional output before, between, and after lines of required output. This additional output must be on a separate line from any required output. Your program must accept the following user input: The player's name (String) The character's name (String) The character's ancestry (String) The character's class (String) The character's level (int) The character's ability scores Strength (int) Dexterity (int) Constitution (int) If all user input is valid, then your program must print the following output: Player: <NAME> Character: <NAME>, level <LEVEL> <ANCESTRY> <CLASS> HP: <HP>, AC: <AC> Ability Scores: Str <STRENGTH SCORE> <STRENGTH MODIFIER> Dex <DEXTERITY SCORE> <DEXTERITY MODIFIER> Con <CONSTITUTION SCORE> <CONSTITUTION MODIFIER> Attacks: <ATTACK1 NAME> <ATTACK1 MODIFIER> <ATTACK2 NAME> <ATTACK2 MODIFIER> (note: some characters only have one attack) Two additional requirements: If a score (strength, dexterity, and constitution) is a single-digit number, then it must be padded with an extra space so that all scores are right-aligned in their column. Each modifier (strength, dexterity, constitution, and attack) must be preceded by a plus or minus sign. Negative modifiers have a minus sign, and nonnegative (which includes zero) modifiers have a plus sign. This reinforces how these numbers are meant to be used: they are usually added to dice rolls and other values rather than used on their own. The ability scores and attacks should also be indented (as shown in the example below), but this will not be checked by the tests. Here is an example of possible user input and the resulting character sheet: Input: Alice
Bob
elf
ranger
4
15
14
9 Output: Player: Alice
Character: Bob, level 4 elf ranger
HP: 28, AC: 17
Ability Scores: Str 15 (+2) Dex 16 (+3) Con 9 (-1)
Attacks: Longsword +4 Longbow +5

24.body: There are two ways for the user to enter invalid input: The user can enter a string or double when you were expecting an integer. If the user entered the word "nine" or the number 12.4 when asked for their level, then this would be the wrong type of input. The user can enter the correct type of input, but not one of the values they were allowed to enter. If the user entered -2 or 50 when asked for their level, then this would be the correct type of input (an integer), but not one of the integers they were allowed to choose for their level (a number from 1 to 20). The first kind of error is more complicated to deal with, and you probably won't learn how to handle those errors until later in the semester. You only need to worry about the second kind of error in this assignment. You can assume that the user will always enter the correct type of value, but your code must check whether it was one of the values they were allowed to choose. If the user enters any invalid input, then your program must print the message ERROR: INVALID INPUT and exit. Here are all of the rules you must enforce when checking the user's input: The level must be an integer from 1 to 20. Each ability score must be an integer from 8 to 15. The ancestry must be either "human", "elf", or "dwarf". The class must be either "fighter", "ranger", or "rogue". You can assume that the user's input for class and ancestry are always lowercase. Your code must correctly handle the lowercase versions of these strings, but it doesn't matter what you do when given other capitalizations (such as "Human", "RANGER", or "DwARf"). You can treat those as invalid and just print an error message (easiest to code but less user-friendly), or you can make your code case-insensitive so that the capitalization does not matter (harder to code but more user-friendly). However you decide to handle the input, the ancestry and class must appear as all lowercase in the program's output.

25.body: This program involves more calculations and variables than the previous program. This section will serve as a reference for all values that are calculated by the program. Before any other calculations, some of the ability scores must be adjusted by the player's ancestry: If the character is a human, increase each ability score by one. If the character is an elf, increase their dexterity score by two. If the character is a dwarf, increase their constitution score by two. Each ability score has an associated number called its modifier . The modifier does not alter the score , it is derived from the score. The srd link has a table showing the modifier associated with each score from 1 to 30, but we can calculate the modifier with a formula. Each ability modifier is calculated by dividing the score by 2 and subtracting 5. The formula should look like this: modifier = score / 2 - 5. It's important that you divide before subtracting because integer division will round towards zero, not down. We could perform a similar calculation by subtracting 10 and then dividing by 2, but this would give the wrong value for odd ability scores below 10. For example, a score of 9 would produce a modifier of 0 when it should have a modifier of -1. The character's HP equals their level multiplied by the sum of their constitution modifier and their "hit die". The hit die is determined by the character's class. A fighter has a hit die of 10, and the other two classes have a hit die of 8. The formula should look like this: hp = level * (conModifier + hitDie). The character's AC (armor class) uses a different formula depending on their class: A fighter's AC is equal to 18 A ranger's AC is equal to 15 plus their dexterity modifier, but their AC cannot be higher than 17 A rogue's AC is equal to 12 plus their dexterity modifier The character's proficiency is not displayed, but it is used to calculate their attack bonus. It uses the formula proficiency = 1 + (level + 3) / 4. Depending on their class, the character has one or two attacks. Each attack has a name and a bonus. The bonus is equal to the character's proficiency bonus plus one of their ability modifiers. A fighter has one attack called Greatsword, which uses their strength modifier A rogue has two attacks: Dagger and Crossbow, which both use their dexterity modifier A ranger has two attacks: Longsword, which uses their strength modifier, and Longbow, which uses their dexterity modifier

3.body: For this project, we will write a program that asks the user for information about a Dungeons and Dragons 5e character and prints them a character sheet.
3.breadcrumbs: Project 1: Character Sheet » Project 1: Character Sheet
3.title: Project 1: Character Sheet

4.body: Dungeons and Dragons is a tabletop roleplaying game (TTRPG). It's probably the most widely-known TTRPG at time of writing, but many others exist . This assignment will use a modified version of some of the character creation rules for D&D 5e. The real rules can be found in the 5e System Reference Document (SRD), which you can read if you're curious and want to learn more. I'm going to summarize a few relevant terms here so that they make more sense when they come up in the assignment later. Some of these are probably obvious, but I don't want to assume any familiarity with games. A player is a real person playing the game. A character is a fictional character in the game. Our program will help a player create their own character for a hypothetical TTRPG, which we might refer to as a player character or PC . A character's class is the role they fill in the game's world. In a game like D&D, which focuses on fighting fantasy monsters, a character's class tells us their role in combat. A wizard casts spells, a rogue sneaks up and surprises enemies, and a fighter wears armor and hits things with a sword. A character's ancestry or race (the term varies by game, but I'll usually go with ancestry when not talking about a specific game) represents what kind of creature they are. Standard D&D races include elf, human, dwarf, goblin, gnome, halfling, and orc. However, depending on the game and who's running it, a TTRPG character could be anything: a ghost, a dragon, a talking bear, or a mannequin. A character's HP or hit points represent how difficult they are to kill or incapacitate in combat. A character's AC or armor class represents how hard they are to hit with an attack. This represents a combination of their ability to avoid attacks (by dodging, blocking, or parrying) and their armor's ability to outright negate an attack that would otherwise hit them. A character's ability scores are numbers that represent a character's strength, cunning, speed, and other qualities that affect most of the actions they can take in the game. A character's ability modifiers are bonuses or penalties derived from their ability scores. The modifiers are the numbers we actually use in most calculations, and the scores only exist to determine the modifiers. At this point, you may be wondering why we bother with the ability scores at all if we don't use them after calculating the modifiers. That's an excellent question! A character's level represents how powerful and experienced they are. In most RPGs, characters gain experience and level up to represent how they've become stronger during their adventures. No, I'm not planning to answer my previous question about why ability scores exist. Yes, it will be on the exam. In addition to standard six-sided dice (referred to as D6 dice), D&D uses several less common dice shapes: D4, D8, D10, D12, and D20.
